		<td width="18"><img src="/Graphics/Interface/Icons/spacer.gif" width=18 height=1 border=0></td>
	
	
		<td>
	




	<font size="-1"><b>More than 130 Educational Conference Sessions</b></font>

	<p>Arlington, VA - Sep, 13 1999
	<BR>
	To help attendees discover the newest trends, strategies and profit opportunities in the consumer technology industry, the 2000 International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology, to be held in Las Vegas, Nev., January 6-9, 2000, will offer more than 130 conference sessions.  International visionaries in content media, delivery and hardware at CES will illustrate new business models and new consumer applications made possible by technology. <P>
Showcasing the growing workstyle and home networking trends in the consumer technology industry, CES will feature four industry leading pioneers as keynoters.  Eric A. Benhamou, chairman and CEO of 3Com Corp.; Scott McNealy, chairman and CEO of Sun Microsystems; Rob Glaser, chairman and CEO of RealNetworks Inc.; and Bill Gates, chairman and CEO of Microsoft Corp., will deliver the Opening Keynote, the Executive Perspective Keynote, the Technology Keynote and the New Millennium Keynote addresses, respectively. <P>
Three power panels and summits also round out the conference program, giving attendees access to the top leaders in retailing, e-commerce and government.  In the <b>E-Commerce Supersession,</b> Jaclyn Easton, author of <i>StrikingItRich.com</i> and columnist for the <i>Los Angeles Times,</i> shares her insights on e-commerce strategy.  Then Easton moderates a panel discussion among online retailers, portals and broadband experts from Cyberian Outpost, RadioShack.com, AOL, Yahoo! Inc. and Amazon.com.  In <b>Retailing for the Digital Age,</b> hear from the biggest names in retailing: Best Buy, Tandy and others. <b>Internet 2000,</b> a half-day summit hosted by Virginia Governor James Gilmore, examines the Internet's impact on American society in the new millennium.  Key state governors, technology leaders and government officials discuss the Internet's global impact and how government and business can work together to enhance the opportunities created by the Internet.   <P>
To make it easier for attendees to find the sessions that cover the product and selling trends they need to know, the CES conference program is divided into 11 session tracks:  <P>
<b>Workstyle Technology:</b> Geared to help retailers gain insight into the small business industry, the telecommuting market and other ways consumers work today, this track highlights the advances in digital imaging, high-speed Internet access, hand-held information devices and other technologies that enable consumers to work when, where and how they wish.  <P>
<b>Lifestyle Technology:</b> Delve into the latest developments occurring in convergent products, digital advances in audio and video products, delivery methods and products/technology for the consumer home market such as DTV, DVD, MP3, CD-R, HAVi, Avio, home networking, copy protection, personalized TV, flat panel TVs, video games and electronic books.  This track will keep attendees up-to-date on what's happening in consumers' homes, what new products are on the horizon, and how to link them all together.  <P>
<b>The Habitech Institute:</b> Sponsored by CEMA, CEDIA, CABA and BICSI, and geared toward custom installers and designers, The Habitech Institute-the trade and training event for integrated home systems-focuses on home theater, home networking, systems integration, home controls and the business of custom installation and design. Learn what the digital home of the future will look like, how to set up systems for multi-family complexes, how to fish wire between floors, how the new powerline networking options work, what's TechHome, where to find quality installers, and what new standards and codes are being written.  <P>
<b>Specialty Audio</b>: In five sessions targeted to the specialty audio community, Audiocafe.com presents a unique atmosphere that encourages participation in town-hall style discussions about exciting and somewhat controversial topics surrounding the industry today. Attendees also can participate in product demonstrations. <P>
<b>Mobile Electronics/Wireless Communications:</b> Hear about the latest technology and killer applications in car audio, wireless phones, mobile data, the Intelligent Transportation Systems Data Bus (IDB), GPS/navigation, vehicle recovery systems, remote starters, auto PC, mobile DVD, digital radio and automotive standards.  Included in the track are three sessions on how retailers can get the most out of the Mobile Electronics Certification Professionals (MECP) program, learn test-taking tips to improve overall scores, and take the test to gain recognition throughout the industry.  <P>
<b>Emerging Technologies:</b> To help engineers and financial/market analysts predict the newest technologies and trends in the consumer technology industry, this conference track focuses on product and content development, delivery issues and how they impact new-to-market companies.  Hear about the latest advances in smart cards, speech technology, computer telephony options, digital interconnectivity devices, Linux and 1394.  See how CEOs and engineering designers can better work together.  Learn how Wall Street evaluates the industry and what are the financial forecasts for the new millennium.  <P>
<b>E-Commerce:</b> Examine the new world of business on the Internet, covering Internet retailing, the basics of e-commerce, the role of TV-based e-commerce, online privacy concerns and using the Internet as a business strategy.   <P>
<b>Retail Management:</b> In these strategic sessions for retail managers and store owners, learn how to explain new technology features to customers so that they walk out the door with purchases in hand.  See how various finance programs can positively affect the bottom line.  Understand the radio and cable TV advertising game.  This conference track gives practical and easy-to-use tools to revamp business-building plans, inventorying methods, merchandising techniques and marketing campaigns.   Included in the track is a special e-commerce session just for retailers on the secrets of Web-based storefronts, presented by noted expert Jaclyn Easton of the <i>Los Angeles Times</i> and <i>StrikingItRich.com.</i> <P>
<b>Executive Forum:</b> Designed to keep CEOs on the fast track, this track covers managing the internal changes the Internet brings to business; understanding how new Washington legislation will affect business; and learning how to make your voice heard on Capitol Hill. <P>
<b>Dataquest Predicts Consumer Technologies:</b> Dataquest, the leading market research and consulting firm for information technology vendors and the financial and investment community, provides an in-depth analysis of four technologies impacting the consumer technology marketplace: digital television, home networking and broadband access, mobile computing and wireless technologies and e-commerce. Learn about technology trends for the next three to five years and how companies can take advantage of the business opportunities being created by the digital technology revolution.  <P>
<b>Digital Hollywood:</b> Devoted to the convergence of entertainment and technology, Digital Hollywood focuses on digital media and content production geared toward computer and Internet companies; telephone companies; broadcast, cable and satellite executives; and entertainment and studio executives. <P>
<b>Keynote Address and Power Panel Dates and Times</b> <P>
Gates, Microsoft, New Millennium Keynote, Wednesday, January 5, 7:00 p.m. <P>
Benhamou, 3Com, Opening Keynote, Thursday, January 6, 8:30 a.m.  <P>
McNealy, Sun, Executive Perspective Keynote, Thursday, January 6, 4:00 p.m. <P>
Glaser, RealNetworks, Technology Keynote, Friday, January 7, 8:30 a.m.  <P>
Internet 2000, Friday, January 7, 11:00 a.m. <P>
E-Commerce Supersession, Friday, January 7, 3:00 p.m. <P>
Retailing in the Digital Age, Saturday, January 8, 8:30 a.m. <P>
All keynotes and the e-commerce supersession will be in the Las Vegas Hilton Theater.  Internet 2000 and Retailing in the Digital Age will be in the Las Vegas Convention Center. <P>
CEMA is a sector of the Electronic Industries Alliance (EIA), the 75-year-old Arlington, Virginia-based trade organization representing all facets of electronics manufacturing.  CEMA represents more than 500 U.S. manufacturers of audio, video, accessories, mobile electronics, communication, information technology and multimedia products that are sold through consumer channels.   <P>
As the sponsor, manager and producer of the International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology, CEMA reinvests all profits from CES into industry services, including technical training and education, product promotion, engineering standards development, market research, and governmental and legal affairs support. <P>
 <P>
